    <property>
      <description>Suppose someone kills 40 people in a mass shooting, and later in turns out that one of the people he killed was planning to kill 100 people himself.&#xd;
&#xd;
It's not reasonable to say "He was right to do it", or even "he was a hero because he saved 60 lives". Why? Because he didn't know that he was killing a bad guy.&#xd;
&#xd;
We need to judge others based on their thinking at the time, not on the end outcome.&#xd;
&#xd;
This is a quite different than "The Ends Justify The Means", which is much more specific.</description>
